# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: runbook-automation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Automation includes the use of various equipment and control systems such as machinery, processes in factories, boilers, and heat-treating ovens, switching on telephone networks, steering, stabilization of ships, aircraft and other applications and vehicles with reduced human intervention.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Examples range from a household thermostat controlling a boiler to a large industrial control system with tens of thousands of input measurements and output control signals.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] In the simplest type of an automatic control loop, a controller compares a measured value of a process with a desired set value and processes the resulting error signal to change some input to the process, in such a way that the process stays at its set point despite disturbances.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] This closed-loop control is an application of negative feedback to a system.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] The mathematical basis of control theory began in the 18th century and advanced rapidly in the 20th.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] The term *automation*, inspired by the earlier word *automatic* (coming from *automaton*), was not widely used before 1947, when Ford established an automation department.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] It was during this time that the industry was rapidly adopting feedback controllers, Technological advancements introduced in the 1930s revolutionized various industries significantly.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] The World Bank's World Development Report of 2019 shows evidence that the new industries and jobs in the technology sector outweigh the economic effects of workers being displaced by automation.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Job losses and downward mobility blamed on automation have been cited as one of many factors in the resurgence of nationalist, protectionist and populist politics in the US, UK and France, among other countries since the 2010s.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] It was a preoccupation of the Greeks and Arabs (in the period between about 300 BC and about 1200 AD) to keep an accurate track of time.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] In Ptolemaic Egypt, about 270 BC, Ctesibius described a float regulator for a water clock, a device not unlike the ball and cock in a modern flush toilet.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] This was the earliest feedback-controlled mechanism.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] The appearance of the mechanical clock in the 14th century made the water clock and its feedback control system obsolete.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] The Persian Banū Mūsā brothers, in their *Book of Ingenious Devices* (850 AD), described a number of automatic controls.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Two-step level controls for fluids, a form of discontinuous variable structure controls, were developed by the Banu Musa brothers.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] They also described a feedback controller.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] The design of feedback control systems up through the Industrial Revolution was by trial-and-error, together with a great deal of engineering intuition.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] It was not until the mid-19th century that the stability of feedback control systems was analyzed using mathematics, the formal language of automatic control theory.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] The centrifugal governor was invented by Christiaan Huygens in the seventeenth century, and used to adjust the gap between millstones.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Another control mechanism was used to tent the sails of windmills.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Also in 1745, Jacques de Vaucanson invented the first automated loom.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Around 1800, Joseph Marie Jacquard created a punch-card system to program looms.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] In 1771 Richard Arkwright invented the first fully automated spinning mill driven by water power, known at the time as the water frame.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] An automatic flour mill was developed by Oliver Evans in 1785, making it the first completely automated industrial process.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Bunce of England in 1784 as part of a model steam crane.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] The centrifugal governor was adopted by James Watt for use on a steam engine in 1788 after Watt's partner Boulton saw one at a flour mill Boulton & Watt were building.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] The governor could not actually hold a set speed; the engine would assume a new constant speed in response to load changes.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] The governor was able to handle smaller variations such as those caused by fluctuating heat load to the boiler.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Also, there was a tendency for oscillation whenever there was a speed change.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] As a consequence, engines equipped with this governor were not suitable for operations requiring constant speed, such as cotton spinning.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Several improvements to the governor, plus improvements to valve cut-off timing on the steam engine, made the engine suitable for most industrial uses before the end of the 19th century.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Advances in the steam engine stayed well ahead of science, both thermodynamics and control theory.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] The governor received relatively little scientific attention until James Clerk Maxwell published a paper that established the beginning of a theoretical basis for understanding control theory.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Relay logic was introduced with factory electrification, which underwent rapid adaptation from 1900 through the 1920s.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Central electric power stations were also undergoing rapid growth and the operation of new high-pressure boilers, steam turbines and electrical substations created a great demand for instruments and controls.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Central control rooms became common in the 1920s, but as late as the early 1930s, most process controls were on-off.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Operators typically monitored charts drawn by recorders that plotted data from instruments.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] To make corrections, operators manually opened or closed valves or turned switches on or off.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Control rooms also used color-coded lights to send signals to workers in the plant to manually make certain changes.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] The development of the electronic amplifier during the 1920s, which was important for long-distance telephony, required a higher signal-to-noise ratio, which was solved by negative feedback noise cancellation.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] This and other telephony applications contributed to the control theory.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] In the 1940s and 1950s, German mathematician Irmgard Flügge-Lotz developed the theory of discontinuous automatic controls, which found military applications during the Second World War to fire control systems and aircraft navigation systems.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Controllers, which were able to make calculated changes in response to deviations from a set point rather than on-off control, began being introduced in the 1930s.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Controllers allowed manufacturing to continue showing productivity gains to offset the declining influence of factory electrification.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Factory productivity was greatly increased by electrification in the 1920s.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Alexander Field notes that spending on non-medical instruments increased significantly from 1929 to 1933 and remained strong thereafter.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] The First and Second World Wars saw major advancements in the field of mass communication and signal processing.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Other key advances in automatic controls include differential equations, stability theory and system theory (1938), frequency domain analysis (1940), ship control (1950), and stochastic analysis (1941).
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] In 1959 Texaco's Port Arthur Refinery became the first chemical plant to use digital control.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Conversion of factories to digital control began to spread rapidly in the 1970s as the price of computer hardware fell.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] The automatic telephone switchboard was introduced in 1892 along with dial telephones.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] By 1929, 31.9% of the Bell system was automatic.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Automatic telephone switching originally used vacuum tube amplifiers and electro-mechanical switches, which consumed a large amount of electricity.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Call volume eventually grew so fast that it was feared the telephone system would consume all electricity production, prompting Bell Labs to begin research on the transistor.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] The logic performed by telephone switching relays was the inspiration for the digital computer.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] The first commercially successful glass bottle-blowing machine was an automatic model introduced in 1905.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] The machine, operated by a two-man crew working 12-hour shifts, could produce 17,280 bottles in 24 hours, compared to 2,880 bottles made by a crew of six men and boys working in a shop for a day.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] The cost of making bottles by machine was 10 to 12 cents per gross compared to $1.80 per gross by the manual glassblowers and helpers.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Sectional electric drives were developed using control theory.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Sectional electric drives are used on different sections of a machine where a precise differential must be maintained between the sections.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] In steel rolling, the metal elongates as it passes through pairs of rollers, which must run at successively faster speeds.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] In paper making paper, the sheet shrinks as it passes around steam-heated drying arranged in groups, which must run at successively slower speeds.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] The first application of a sectional electric drive was on a paper machine in 1919.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] One of the most important developments in the steel industry during the 20th century was continuous wide strip rolling, developed by Armco in 1928.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Before automation, many chemicals were made in batches.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] In 1930, with the widespread use of instruments and the emerging use of controllers, the founder of Dow Chemical Co. was advocating continuous production.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Self-acting machine tools that displaced hand dexterity so they could be operated by boys and unskilled laborers were developed by James Nasmyth in the 1840s.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Machine tools were automated with Numerical control (NC) using punched paper tape in the 1950s.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] This soon evolved into computerized numerical control (CNC).
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Today extensive automation is practiced in practically every type of manufacturing and assembly process.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Robots are especially useful in hazardous applications like automobile spray painting.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Robots are also used to assemble electronic circuit boards.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Automotive welding is done with robots and automatic welders are used in applications like pipelines.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] With the advent of the space age in 1957, controls design, particularly in the United States, turned away from the frequency-domain techniques of classical control theory and backed into the differential equation techniques of the late 19th century, which were couched in the time domain.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] During the 1940s and 1950s, German mathematician Irmgard Flugge-Lotz developed the theory of discontinuous automatic control, which became widely used in hysteresis control systems such as navigation systems, fire-control systems, and electronics.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Through Flugge-Lotz and others, the modern era saw time-domain design for nonlinear systems (1961), navigation (1960), optimal control and estimation theory (1962), nonlinear control theory (1969), digital control and filtering theory (1974), and the personal computer (1983).
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Perhaps the most cited advantage of automation in industry is that it is associated with faster production and cheaper labor costs.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Another benefit could be that it replaces hard, physical, or monotonous work.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Additionally, tasks that take place in hazardous environments or that are otherwise beyond human capabilities can be done by machines, as machines can operate even under extreme temperatures or in atmospheres that are radioactive or toxic.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] They can also be maintained with simple quality checks.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] However, at the time being, not all tasks can be automated, and some tasks are more expensive to automate than others.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Initial costs of installing the machinery in factory settings are high, and failure to maintain a system could result in the loss of the product itself.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Automation primarily describes machines replacing human action, but it is also loosely associated with mechanization, machines replacing human labor.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] The paradox of automation says that the more efficient the automated system, the more crucial the human contribution of the operators.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Humans are less involved, but their involvement becomes more critical.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Lisanne Bainbridge, a cognitive psychologist, identified these issues notably in her widely cited paper "Ironies of Automation." If an automated system has an error, it will multiply that error until it is fixed or shut down.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] A fatal example of this was Air France Flight 447, where a failure of automation put the pilots into a manual situation they were not prepared for.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Many roles for humans in industrial processes presently lie beyond the scope of automation.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Human-level pattern recognition, language comprehension, and language production ability are well beyond the capabilities of modern mechanical and computer systems (but see *Watson computer*).
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Tasks requiring subjective assessment or synthesis of complex sensory data, such as scents and sounds, as well as high-level tasks such as strategic planning, currently require human expertise.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] In many cases, the use of humans is more cost-effective than mechanical approaches even where the automation of industrial tasks is possible.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Therefore, algorithmic management as the digital rationalization of human labor instead of its substitution has emerged as an alternative technological strategy.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Overcoming these obstacles is a theorized path to post-scarcity economics.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] As of 2025-2026, real-world deployment of advanced robotics has revealed critical infrastructure limitations, such as "battery-life bottlenecks" (typically 2–4 hours of operation per charge) and the requirement for high-bandwidth Wi-Fi and specialized flooring for reliable function.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Additionally, robots continue to struggle with unpredictable human-made obstructions, which still necessitate human intervention to maintain operational flow.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Increased automation often causes workers to feel anxious about losing their jobs as technology renders their skills or experience unnecessary.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Early in the Industrial Revolution, when inventions like the steam engine were making some job categories expendable, workers forcefully resisted these changes.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Luddites, for instance, were English textile workers who protested the introduction of weaving machines by destroying them.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] More recently, some residents of Chandler, Arizona, have slashed tires and pelted rocks at a self-driving car, in protest over the cars' perceived threat to human safety and job prospects.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] The relative anxiety about automation reflected in opinion polls seems to correlate closely with the strength of organized labor in that region or nation.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] According to one estimate, 47% of all current jobs in the US have the potential to be fully automated by 2033.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Furthermore, wages and educational attainment appear to be strongly negatively correlated with an occupation's risk of being automated.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Erik Brynjolfsson and Andrew McAfee argue that "there's never been a better time to be a worker with special skills or the right education, because these people can use technology to create and capture value.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Research by Carl Benedikt Frey and Michael Osborne of the Oxford Martin School argued that employees engaged in "tasks following well-defined procedures that can easily be performed by sophisticated algorithms" are at risk of displacement, and 47% of jobs in the US were at risk.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] The study, released as a working paper in 2013 and published in 2017, predicted that automation would put low-paid physical occupations most at risk, by surveying a group of colleagues on their opinions.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] However, according to a study published in *McKinsey Quarterly* in 2015 the impact of computerization in most cases is not the replacement of employees but the automation of portions of the tasks they perform.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] The methodology of the McKinsey study has been heavily criticized for being intransparent and relying on subjective assessments.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] The methodology of Frey and Osborne has been subjected to criticism, as lacking evidence, historical awareness, or credible methodology.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Additionally, the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) found that across the 21 OECD countries, 9% of jobs are automatable.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Based on a formula by Gilles Saint-Paul, an economist at Toulouse 1 University, the demand for unskilled human capital declines at a slower rate than the demand for skilled human capital increases.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] In the long run and for society as a whole it has led to cheaper products, lower average work hours, and new industries forming (i.e., robotics industries, computer industries, design industries).
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] These new industries provide many high salary skill-based jobs to the economy.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] By 2030, between 3 and 14 percent of the global workforce will be forced to switch job categories due to automation eliminating jobs in an entire sector.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] While the number of jobs lost to automation is often offset by jobs gained from technological advances, the same type of job loss is not the same one replaced and that leading to increasing unemployment in the lower-middle class.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] This occurs largely in the US and developed countries where technological advances contribute to higher demand for highly skilled labor but demand for middle-wage labor continues to fall.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Economists call this trend "income polarization" where unskilled labor wages are driven down and skilled labor is driven up and it is predicted to continue in developed economies.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Lights-out manufacturing is a production system with no human workers, to eliminate labor costs.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] It grew in popularity in the U.S. when General Motors in 1982 implemented humans "hands-off" manufacturing to "replace risk-averse bureaucracy with automation and robots".
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] However, the factory never reached full "lights out" status.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] The costs of automation to the environment are different depending on the technology, product or engine automated.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] There are automated engines that consume more energy resources from the Earth in comparison with previous engines and vice versa.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Hazardous operations, such as oil refining, the manufacturing of industrial chemicals, and all forms of metal working, were always early contenders for automation.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] The automation of vehicles could prove to have a substantial impact on the environment, although the nature of this impact could be beneficial or harmful depending on several factors.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Because automated vehicles are much less likely to get into accidents compared to human-driven vehicles, some precautions built into current models (such as anti-lock brakes or laminated glass) would not be required for self-driving versions.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Removal of these safety features reduces the weight of the vehicle, and coupled with more precise acceleration and braking, as well as fuel-efficient route mapping, can increase fuel economy and reduce emissions.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Despite this, some researchers theorize that an increase in the production of self-driving cars could lead to a boom in vehicle ownership and usage, which could potentially negate any environmental benefits of self-driving cars if they are used more frequently.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Automation of homes and home appliances is also thought to impact the environment.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] This study, along with others, indicated that the smart home's ability to monitor and adjust consumption levels would reduce unnecessary energy usage.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] However, some research suggests that smart homes might not be as efficient as non-automated homes.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] A more recent study has indicated that, while monitoring and adjusting consumption levels do decrease unnecessary energy use, this process requires monitoring systems that also consume an amount of energy.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] The energy required to run these systems sometimes negates their benefits, resulting in little to no ecological benefit.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Another major shift in automation is the increased demand for flexibility and convertibility in manufacturing processes.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Manufacturers are increasingly demanding the ability to easily switch from manufacturing Product A to manufacturing Product B without having to completely rebuild the production lines.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Flexibility and distributed processes have led to the introduction of Automated Guided Vehicles with Natural Features Navigation.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Former analog-based instrumentation was replaced by digital equivalents which can be more accurate and flexible, and offer greater scope for more sophisticated configuration, parametrization, and operation.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] This was accompanied by the fieldbus revolution which provided a networked (i.e. a single cable) means of communicating between control systems and field-level instrumentation, eliminating hard-wiring.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Discrete manufacturing plants adopted these technologies fast.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] The more conservative process industries with their longer plant life cycles have been slower to adopt and analog-based measurement and control still dominate.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] The growing use of Industrial Ethernet on the factory floor is pushing these trends still further, enabling manufacturing plants to be integrated more tightly within the enterprise, via the internet if necessary.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Global competition has also increased demand for Reconfigurable Manufacturing Systems.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Engineers can now have numerical control over automated devices.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] The result has been a rapidly expanding range of applications and human activities.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Computer-aided technologies (or CAx) now serve as the basis for mathematical and organizational tools used to create complex systems.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Notable examples of CAx include computer-aided design (CAD software) and computer-aided manufacturing (CAM software).
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] The improved design, analysis, and manufacture of products enabled by CAx has been beneficial for industry.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Information technology, together with industrial machinery and processes, can assist in the design, implementation, and monitoring of control systems.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] One example of an industrial control system is a programmable logic controller (PLC).
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] PLCs are specialized hardened computers which are frequently used to synchronize the flow of inputs from (physical) sensors and events with the flow of outputs to actuators and events.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Human-machine interfaces (HMI) or computer human interfaces (CHI), formerly known as *man-machine interfaces*, are usually employed to communicate with PLCs and other computers.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Service personnel who monitor and control through HMIs can be called by different names.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] In the industrial process and manufacturing environments, they are called operators or something similar.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] In boiler houses and central utility departments, they are called *stationary engineers*.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Host simulation software (HSS) is a commonly used testing tool that is used to test the equipment software.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] HSS is used to test equipment performance concerning factory automation standards (timeouts, response time, processing time).
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Cognitive automation, as a subset of AI, is an emerging genus of automation enabled by cognitive computing.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Its primary concern is the automation of clerical tasks and workflows that consist of structuring unstructured data.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Cognitive automation relies on multiple disciplines: natural language processing, real-time computing, machine learning algorithms, big data analytics, and evidence-based learning.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Artificially intelligent computer-aided design (CAD) can use text-to-3D, image-to-3D, and video-to-3D to automate in 3D modeling.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] AI CAD libraries could also be developed using linked open data of schematics and diagrams.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Ai CAD assistants are used as tools to help streamline workflow.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Technologies like solar panels, wind turbines, and other renewable energy sources—together with smart grids, micro-grids, battery storage—can automate power production.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Many agricultural operations are automated with machinery and equipment to improve their diagnosis, decision-making and/or performing.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Agricultural automation can relieve the drudgery of agricultural work, improve the timeliness and precision of agricultural operations, raise productivity and resource-use efficiency, build resilience, and improve food quality and safety.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Increased productivity can free up labour, allowing agricultural households to spend more time elsewhere.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] The technological evolution in agriculture has resulted in progressive shifts to digital equipment and robotics.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Motorized mechanization using engine power automates the performance of agricultural operations such as ploughing and milking.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] With digital automation technologies, it also becomes possible to automate diagnosis and decision-making of agricultural operations.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] For example, autonomous crop robots can harvest and seed crops, while drones can gather information to help automate input application.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Motorized mechanization has generally increased in recent years.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Sub-Saharan Africa is the only region where the adoption of motorized mechanization has stalled over the past decades.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Automation technologies are increasingly used for managing livestock, though evidence on adoption is lacking.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Adoption is likely mostly in Northern Europe, and likely almost absent in low- and middle-income countries.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Automated feeding machines for both cows and poultry also exist, but data and evidence regarding their adoption trends and drivers is likewise scarce.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Many supermarkets and even smaller stores are rapidly introducing self-checkout systems reducing the need for employing checkout workers.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] In the U.S., the retail industry employs 15.9 million people as of 2017 (around 1 in 9 Americans in the workforce).
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Globally, an estimated 192 million workers could be affected by automation according to research by Eurasia Group.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Online shopping could be considered a form of automated retail as the payment and checkout are through an automated online transaction processing system, with the share of online retail accounting jumping from 5.1% in 2011 to 8.3% in 2016.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] However, two-thirds of books, music, and films are now purchased online.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] In addition, automation and online shopping could reduce demands for shopping malls, and retail property, which in the United States is currently estimated to account for 31% of all commercial property or around 7 billion square feet (650 million square metres).
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Amazon has gained much of the growth in recent years for online shopping, accounting for half of the growth in online retail in 2016.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Other forms of automation can also be an integral part of online shopping, for example, the deployment of automated warehouse robotics such as that applied by Amazon using Kiva Systems.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] The food retail industry has started to apply automation to the ordering process; McDonald's has introduced touch screen ordering and payment systems in many of its restaurants, reducing the need for as many cashier employees.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] The University of Texas at Austin has introduced fully automated cafe retail locations.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Some cafes and restaurants have utilized mobile and tablet "apps" to make the ordering process more efficient by customers ordering and paying on their device.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Some restaurants have automated food delivery to tables of customers using a conveyor belt system.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] The use of robots is sometimes employed to replace waiting staff.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Automation in construction is the combination of methods, processes, and systems that allow for greater machine autonomy in construction activities.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Construction automation may have multiple goals, including but not limited to, reducing jobsite injuries, decreasing activity completion times, and assisting with quality control and quality assurance.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Automated mining involves the removal of human labor from the mining process.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] The mining industry is currently in the transition towards automation.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Currently, it can still require a large amount of human capital, particularly in the third world where labor costs are low so there is less incentive for increasing efficiency through automation.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] The Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA) started the research and development of automated visual surveillance and monitoring (VSAM) program, between 1997 and 1999, and airborne video surveillance (AVS) programs, from 1998 to 2002.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Currently, there is a major effort underway in the vision community to develop a fully-automated tracking surveillance system.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Automated video surveillance monitors people and vehicles in real-time within a busy environment.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Existing automated surveillance systems are based on the environment they are primarily designed to observe, i.e., indoor, outdoor or airborne, the number of sensors that the automated system can handle and the mobility of sensors, i.e., stationary camera vs. mobile camera.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] The purpose of a surveillance system is to record properties and trajectories of objects in a given area, generate warnings or notify the designated authorities in case of occurrence of particular events.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] As demands for safety and mobility have grown and technological possibilities have multiplied, interest in automation has grown.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Seeking to accelerate the development and introduction of fully automated vehicles and highways, the U.S.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Congress authorized more than $650 million over six years for intelligent transport systems (ITS) and demonstration projects in the 1991 *Intermodal Surface Transportation Efficiency Act* (ISTEA).
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Full automation commonly defined as requiring no control or very limited control by the driver; such automation would be accomplished through a combination of sensor, computer, and communications systems in vehicles and along the roadway.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Fully automated driving would, in theory, allow closer vehicle spacing and higher speeds, which could enhance traffic capacity in places where additional road building is physically impossible, politically unacceptable, or prohibitively expensive.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Automated controls also might enhance road safety by reducing the opportunity for driver error, which causes a large share of motor vehicle crashes.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Other potential benefits include improved air quality (as a result of more-efficient traffic flows), increased fuel economy, and spin-off technologies generated during research and development related to automated highway systems.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Automated waste collection trucks prevent the need for as many workers as well as easing the level of labor required to provide the service.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Business process automation (BPA) is the technology-enabled automation of complex business processes.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] It can help to streamline a business for simplicity, achieve digital transformation, increase service quality, improve service delivery or contain costs.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] BPA consists of integrating applications, restructuring labor resources and using software applications throughout the organization.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Robotic process automation (RPA; or RPAAI for self-guided RPA 2.0) is an emerging field within BPA and uses AI.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] BPAs can be implemented in a number of business areas including recruitment, marketing, sales and workflow.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Home automation (also called **domotics**) designates an emerging practice of increased automation of household appliances and features in residential dwellings, particularly through electronic means that allow for things impracticable, overly expensive or simply not possible in recent past decades.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] The rise in the usage of home automation solutions has taken a turn reflecting the increased dependency of people on such automation solutions.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] However, the increased comfort that gets added through these automation solutions is remarkable.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Automation is essential for many scientific and clinical applications.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Therefore, automation has been extensively employed in laboratories.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] From as early as 1980 fully automated laboratories have already been working.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] However, automation has not become widespread in laboratories due to its high cost.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] This may change with the ability of integrating low-cost devices with standard laboratory equipment.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Autosamplers are common devices used in laboratory automation.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Logistics automation is the application of computer software or automated machinery to improve the efficiency of logistics operations.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Typically this refers to operations within a warehouse or distribution center, with broader tasks undertaken by supply chain engineering systems and enterprise resource planning systems.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Industrial automation deals primarily with the automation of manufacturing, quality control, and material handling processes.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] General-purpose controllers for industrial processes include programmable logic controllers, stand-alone I/O modules, and computers.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Industrial automation is to replace the human action and manual command-response activities with the use of mechanized equipment and logical programming commands.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] One trend is increased use of machine vision to provide automatic inspection and robot guidance functions, another is a continuing increase in the use of robots.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Industrial automation is simply required in industries.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] The rise of industrial automation is directly tied to the "Fourth Industrial Revolution", which is better known now as Industry 4.0.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Originating from Germany, Industry 4.0 encompasses numerous devices, concepts, and machines, as well as the advancement of the industrial internet of things (IIoT).
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] An "Internet of Things is a seamless integration of diverse physical objects in the Internet through a virtual representation".
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] These new advancements have drawn attention to the world of automation and have shown ways for it to increase productivity and efficiency in machinery and manufacturing facilities.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Industry 4.0 works with the IIoT and software/hardware to connect in a way that (through communication technologies) add enhancements and improve manufacturing processes.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Being able to create more advanced manufacturing is now possible with these new technologies.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] It opens up an improved manufacturing platform.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Implementation of systems such as SCADA is an example of software that takes place in industrial automation today.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] SCADA is a supervisory data collection software, just one of the many used in industrial automation.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Industry 4.0 covers many areas in manufacturing.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Industrial robotics is a sub-branch in industrial automation that aids in various manufacturing processes.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Such manufacturing processes include machining, welding, painting, assembling and material handling to name a few.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Industrial robots use various mechanical, electrical as well as software systems to allow for high precision, accuracy and speed that far exceed any human performance.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] The birth of industrial robots came shortly after World War II as the U.S. saw the need for a quicker way to produce industrial and consumer goods.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Servos, digital logic and solid-state electronics allowed engineers to build better and faster systems and over time these systems were improved and revised to the point where a single robot is capable of running 24 hours a day with little or no maintenance.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] In 1997, there were 700,000 industrial robots in use, the number has risen to 1.8M in 2017 In recent years, AI with robotics is also used in creating an automatic labeling solution, using robotic arms as the automatic label applicator, and AI for learning and detecting the products to be labelled.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Industrial automation incorporates programmable logic controllers in the manufacturing process.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Programmable logic controllers (PLCs) use a processing system which allows for variation of controls of inputs and outputs using simple programming.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] PLCs make use of programmable memory, storing instructions and functions like logic, sequencing, timing, counting, etc.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Using a logic-based language, a PLC can receive a variety of inputs and return a variety of logical outputs, the input devices being sensors and output devices being motors, valves, etc.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] PLCs are similar to computers, however, while computers are optimized for calculations, PLCs are optimized for control tasks and use in industrial environments.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] They are built so that only basic logic-based programming knowledge is needed and to handle vibrations, high temperatures, humidity, and noise.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] The greatest advantage PLCs offer is their flexibility.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] With the same basic controllers, a PLC can operate a range of different control systems.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] PLCs make it unnecessary to rewire a system to change the control system.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] This flexibility leads to a cost-effective system for complex and varied control systems.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] PLCs can range from small "building brick" devices with tens of I/O in a housing integral with the processor, to large rack-mounted modular devices with a count of thousands of I/O, and which are often networked to other PLC and SCADA systems.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] They can be designed for multiple arrangements of digital and analog inputs and outputs (I/O), extended temperature ranges, immunity to electrical noise, and resistance to vibration and impact.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Programs to control machine operation are typically stored in battery-backed-up or non-volatile memory.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] It was from the automotive industry in the United States that the PLC was born.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Before the PLC, control, sequencing, and safety interlock logic for manufacturing automobiles was mainly composed of relays, cam timers, drum sequencers, and dedicated closed-loop controllers.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Since these could number in the hundreds or even thousands, the process for updating such facilities for the yearly model change-over was very time-consuming and expensive, as electricians needed to individually rewire the relays to change their operational characteristics.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] When digital computers became available, being general-purpose programmable devices, they were soon applied to control sequential and combinatorial logic in industrial processes.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] However, these early computers required specialist programmers and stringent operating environmental control for temperature, cleanliness, and power quality.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] To meet these challenges, the PLC was developed with several key attributes.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] It would tolerate the shop-floor environment, it would support discrete (bit-form) input and output in an easily extensible manner, it would not require years of training to use, and it would permit its operation to be monitored.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Since many industrial processes have timescales easily addressed by millisecond response times, modern (fast, small, reliable) electronics greatly facilitate building reliable controllers, and performance could be traded off for reliability.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Agent-assisted automation refers to automation used by call center agents to handle customer inquiries.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] The key benefit of agent-assisted automation is compliance and error-proofing.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] Agents are sometimes not fully trained or they forget or ignore key steps in the process.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] The use of automation ensures that what is supposed to happen on the call actually does, every time.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p01] There are two basic types: desktop automation and automated voice solutions.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p02] Fundamentally, there are two types of control loop: *open-loop control* (feedforward), and *closed-loop control* (feedback).
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p02] One of the simplest types of control is *on-off* control.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p02] An example is a thermostat used on household appliances which either open or close an electrical contact.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p02] Sequence control, in which a programmed sequence of *discrete* operations is performed, often based on system logic that involves system states.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p02] An elevator control system is an example of sequence control.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p02] A proportional–integral–derivative controller (PID controller) is a control loop feedback mechanism (controller) widely used in industrial control systems.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p02] The theoretical understanding and application date from the 1920s, and they are implemented in nearly all analog control systems; originally in mechanical controllers, and then using discrete electronics and latterly in industrial process computers.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p02] Sequential control may be either to a fixed sequence or to a logical one that will perform different actions depending on various system states.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p02] An example of an adjustable but otherwise fixed sequence is a timer on a lawn sprinkler.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p02] States refer to the various conditions that can occur in a use or sequence scenario of the system.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p02] An example is an elevator, which uses logic based on the system state to perform certain actions in response to its state and operator input.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p02] For example, if the operator presses the floor n button, the system will respond depending on whether the elevator is stopped or moving, going up or down, or if the door is open or closed, and other conditions.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p02] Early development of sequential control was relay logic, by which electrical relays engage electrical contacts which either start or interrupt power to a device.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p02] Relays were first used in telegraph networks before being developed for controlling other devices, such as when starting and stopping industrial-sized electric motors or opening and closing solenoid valves.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p02] Using relays for control purposes allowed event-driven control, where actions could be triggered out of sequence, in response to external events.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p02] These were more flexible in their response than the rigid single-sequence cam timers.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p02] More complicated examples involved maintaining safe sequences for devices such as swing bridge controls, where a lock bolt needed to be disengaged before the bridge could be moved, and the lock bolt could not be released until the safety gates had already been closed.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p02] The total number of relays and cam timers can number into the hundreds or even thousands in some factories.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p02] Early programming techniques and languages were needed to make such systems manageable, one of the first being ladder logic, where diagrams of the interconnected relays resembled the rungs of a ladder.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p02] Special computers called programmable logic controllers were later designed to replace these collections of hardware with a single, more easily re-programmed unit.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p02] In a typical hard-wired motor start and stop circuit (called a *control circuit*) a motor is started by pushing a "Start" or "Run" button that activates a pair of electrical relays.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p02] The "lock-in" relay locks in contacts that keep the control circuit energized when the push-button is released.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p02] (The start button is a normally open contact and the stop button is a normally closed contact.) Another relay energizes a switch that powers the device that throws the motor starter switch (three sets of contacts for three-phase industrial power) in the main power circuit.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p02] Large motors use high voltage and experience high in-rush current, making speed important in making and breaking contact.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p02] This can be dangerous for personnel and property with manual switches.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p02] The "lock-in" contacts in the start circuit and the main power contacts for the motor are held engaged by their respective electromagnets until a "stop" or "off" button is pressed, which de-energizes the lock in relay.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p02] Commonly interlocks are added to a control circuit.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p02] Suppose that the motor in the example is powering machinery that has a critical need for lubrication.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p02] In this case, an interlock could be added to ensure that the oil pump is running before the motor starts.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p02] Timers, limit switches, and electric eyes are other common elements in control circuits.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p02] Solenoid valves are widely used on compressed air or hydraulic fluid for powering actuators on mechanical components.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p02] Computers can perform both sequential control and feedback control, and typically a single computer will do both in an industrial application.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p02] Programmable logic controllers (PLCs) are a type of special-purpose microprocessor that replaced many hardware components such as timers and drum sequencers used in relay logic–type systems.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p02] General-purpose process control computers have increasingly replaced stand-alone controllers, with a single computer able to perform the operations of hundreds of controllers.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p02] Process control computers can process data from a network of PLCs, instruments, and controllers to implement typical (such as PID) control of many individual variables or, in some cases, to implement complex control algorithms using multiple inputs and mathematical manipulations.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p02] They can also analyze data and create real-time graphical displays for operators and run reports for operators, engineers, and management.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p02] Control of an automated teller machine (ATM) is an example of an interactive process in which a computer will perform a logic-derived response to a user selection based on information retrieved from a networked database.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p02] The ATM process has similarities with other online transaction processes.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p02] The different logical responses are called *scenarios*.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p02] Such processes are typically designed with the aid of use cases and flowcharts, which guide the writing of the software code.
[src:runbook-automation/automation-p02] The earliest feedback control mechanism was the water clock invented by Greek engineer Ctesibius (285–222 BC).
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Google SREs spend much of their time optimizing—squeezing every bit of performance from a system through project work and developer collaboration.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] But the scope of optimization isn’t limited to compute resources: it’s also important that SREs optimize how they spend their time.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Primarily, we want to avoid performing tasks classified as toil.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] For a comprehensive discussion of toil, see Chapter 5 in Site Reliability Engineering.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] For the purposes of this chapter, we’ll define toil as the repetitive, predictable, constant stream of tasks related to maintaining a service.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Toil is seemingly unavoidable for any team that manages a production service.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] System maintenance inevitably demands a certain amount of rollouts, upgrades, restarts, alert triaging, and so forth.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] These activities can quickly consume a team if left unchecked and unaccounted for.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Google limits the time SRE teams spend on operational work (including both toil- and non-toil-intensive work) at 50% (for more context on why, see Chapter 5 in our first book).
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] While this target may not be appropriate for your organization, there’s still an advantage to placing an upper bound on toil, as identifying and quantifying toil is the first step toward optimizing your team’s time.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Toil tends to fall on a spectrum measured by the following characteristics, which are described in our first book.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Sources of toil may not always meet all of these criteria, but remember that toil comes in many forms.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] In addition to the preceding traits, consider the effect a particular piece of work has on team morale.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Do people enjoy doing a task and find it rewarding, or is it the type of work that’s often neglected because it’s viewed as boring or unrewarding?2 Toil can slowly deflate team morale.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Time spent working on toil is generally time not spent thinking critically or expressing creativity; reducing toil is an acknowledgment that an engineer’s effort is better utilized in areas where human judgment and expression are possible.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] How do you know how much of your operational work is toil?
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] And once you’ve decided to take action to reduce toil, how do you know if your efforts were successful or justified?
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Many SRE teams answer these questions with a combination of experience and intuition.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] While such tactics might produce results, we can improve upon them.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Experience and intuition are not repeatable, objective, or transferable.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Members of the same team or organization often arrive at different conclusions regarding the magnitude of engineering effort lost to toil, and therefore prioritize remediation efforts differently.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Furthermore, toil reduction efforts can span quarters or even years (as demonstrated by some of the case studies in this chapter), during which time team priorities and personnel can change.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] To maintain focus and justify cost over the long term, you need an objective measure of progress.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Usually, teams must choose a toil-reduction project from several candidates.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] An objective measure of toil allows your team to evaluate the severity of the problems and prioritize them to achieve maximum return on engineering investment.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Before beginning toil reduction projects, it’s important to analyze cost versus benefit and to confirm that the time saved through eliminating toil will (at minimum) be proportional to the time invested in first developing and then maintaining an automated solution (Figure 6-1).
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Projects that look “unprofitable” from a simplistic comparison of hours saved versus hours invested might still be well worth undertaking because of the many indirect or intangible benefits of automation.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] So how do we recommend you measure toil?
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Select an appropriate unit of measure that expresses the amount of human effort applied to this toil.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Minutes and hours are a natural choice because they are objective and universally understood.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Be sure to account for the cost of context switching.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] For efforts that are distributed or fragmented, a different well-understood bucket of human effort may be more appropriate.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Some examples of units of measure include an applied patch, a completed ticket, a manual production change, a predictable email exchange, or a hardware operation.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] As long as the unit is objective, consistent, and well understood, it can serve as a measurement of toil.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Track these measurements continuously before, during, and after toil reduction efforts.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Streamline the measurement process using tools or scripts so that collecting these measurements doesn’t create additional toil!
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Toil, like a crumbling bridge or a leaky dam, hides in the banal day to day.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] The categories in this section aren’t exhaustive, but represent some common categories of toil.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Many of these categories seem like “normal” engineering work, and they are.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] It’s helpful to think of toil as a spectrum rather than a binary classification.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] This is probably the most common source of toil.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Maybe your team manages some computing resource—compute, storage, network, load balancers, databases, and so on—along with the hardware that supplies that resource.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] You deal with onboarding users, configuring and securing their machines, performing software updates, and adding and removing servers to moderate capacity.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] You also work to minimize cost or waste of that resource.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Your team is the human interface to the machine, typically interacting with internal customers who file tickets for their needs.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Your organization may even have multiple ticketing systems and work intake systems.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Ticket toil is a bit insidious because ticket-driven business processes usually accomplish their goal.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Users get what they want, and because the toil is typically dispersed evenly across the team, the toil doesn’t loudly and obviously call for remediation.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Wherever a ticket-driven process exists, there’s a chance that toil is quietly accumulating nearby.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Even if you’re not explicitly planning to automate a process, you can still perform process improvement work such as simplification and streamlining—the processes will be easier to automate later, and easier to manage in the meantime.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Interrupts are a general class of time-sensitive janitorial tasks that keep systems running.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] For example, you may need to fix an acute shortage of some resource (disk, memory, I/O) by manually freeing up disk space or restarting applications that are leaking memory.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] You may be filing requests to replace hard drives, “kicking” unresponsive systems, or manually tweaking capacity to meet current or expected loads.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Generally, interrupts take attention away from more important work.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] In many organizations, deployment tools automatically shepherd releases from development to production.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Even with automation, thorough code coverage, code reviews, and numerous forms of automated testing, this process doesn’t always go smoothly.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Depending on the tooling and release cadence, release requests, rollbacks, emergency patches, and repetitive or manual configuration changes, releases may still generate toil.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] You may find yourself frequently migrating from one technology to another.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] You perform this work manually or with limited scripting because, hopefully, you’re only going to move from X to Y once.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Migrations come in many forms, but some examples include changes of data stores, cloud vendors, source code control systems, application libraries, and tooling.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] If you approach a large-scale migration manually, the migration quite likely involves toil.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] You may be inclined to execute the migration manually because it’s a one-time effort.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] While you might even be tempted to view it as “project work” rather than “toil”, migration work can also meet many of the criteria of toil.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Technically, modifying backup tooling for one database to work with another is software development, but this work is basically just refactoring code to replace one interface with another.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] This work is repetitive, and to a large extent, the business value of the backup tooling is the same as before.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Whether you own hardware or use an infrastructure provider (cloud), cost engineering and capacity planning usually entail some associated toil.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Distributed microservice architectures are now common, and as systems become more distributed, new failure modes arise.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] An organization may not have the resources to build sophisticated distributed tracing, high-fidelity monitoring, or detailed dashboards.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Even if the business does have these tools, they might not work with all systems.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Troubleshooting may even require logging in to individual systems and writing ad hoc log analytics queries with scripting tools.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Troubleshooting itself isn’t inherently bad, but you should aim to focus your energy on novel failure modes—not the same type of failure every week caused by brittle system architecture.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] With each new critical upstream dependency of availability P, availability decreases by 1 – P due to the combined chance of failure.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] We’ve found that performing toil management is critical if you’re operating a production system of any scale.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Once you identify and quantify toil, you need a plan for eliminating it.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] These efforts may take weeks or quarters to accomplish, so it’s important to have a solid overarching strategy.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Eliminating toil at its source is the optimal solution, but if doing so isn’t possible, then you must handle the toil by other means.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Before we dive into the specifics of two in-depth case studies, this section provides some general strategies to consider when you’re planning a toil reduction effort.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] As you’ll observe across the two stories, the nuances of toil vary from team to team (and from company to company), but regardless of specificity, some common tactics ring true for organizations of any size or flavor.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Each of the following patterns is illustrated in a concrete way in at least one of the subsequent case studies.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] We recommend that you adopt a data-driven approach to identify and compare sources of toil, make objective remedial decisions, and quantify the time saved (return on investment) by toil reduction projects.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] If your team is experiencing toil overload, treat toil reduction as its own project.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Google SRE teams often track toil in bugs and rank toil according to the cost to fix it and the time saved by doing so.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] See the section Measuring Toil for techniques and guidance.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] The optimal strategy for handling toil is to eliminate it at the source.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Before investing effort in managing the toil generated by your existing systems and processes, examine whether you can reduce or eliminate that toil by changing the system.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] A team that runs a system in production has invaluable experience with how that system works.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] They know the quirks and tedious bits that cause the most amount of toil.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] An SRE team should apply this knowledge by working with product development teams to develop operationally friendly software that is not only less toilsome, but also more scalable, secure, and resilient.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] A toil-laden team should make data-driven decisions about how best to spend their time and engineering effort.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] In our experience, while it may seem counterproductive, rejecting a toil-intensive task should be the first option you consider.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] For a given set of toil, analyze the cost of responding to the toil versus not doing so.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Another tactic is to intentionally delay the toil so that tasks accumulate for batch or parallelized processing.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Working with toil in larger aggregates reduces interrupts and helps you identify patterns of toil, which you can then target for elimination.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] As discussed in Implementing SLOs, services should have a documented service level objective (SLO).
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] A well-defined SLO enables engineers to make informed decisions.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] For example, you might ignore certain operational tasks if doing so does not consume or exceed the service’s error budget.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] An SLO that focuses on overall service health, rather than individual devices, is more flexible and sustainable as the service grows.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] See Implementing SLOs for guidance on writing effective SLOs.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] If you have a particularly complex business problem with many edge cases or types of requests, consider a partially automated approach as an interim step toward full automation.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] In this approach, your service receives structured data—usually via a defined API—but engineers may still handle some of the resulting operations.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Even if some manual effort remains, this “engineer behind the curtain” approach allows you to incrementally move toward full automation.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Use customer input to progress toward a more uniform way of collecting this data; by decreasing free-form requests, you can move closer to handling all requests programmatically.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] This approach can save back and forth with customers (who now have clear indicators of the information you need) and save you from overengineering a big-bang solution before you’ve fully mapped and understood the domain.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Once you’ve defined your service offering via a typed interface (see Start with Human-Backed Interfaces), move to providing self-service methods for users.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] You can provide a web form, binary or script, API, or even just documentation that tells users how to issue pull requests to your service’s configuration files.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] For example, rather than asking engineers to file a ticket to provision a new virtual machine for their development work, give them a simple web form or script that triggers the provisioning.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Allow the script to gracefully degrade to a ticket for specialized requests or if a failure occurs.4 Human-backed interfaces are a good start in the war against toil, but service owners should always aim to make their offerings self-service where possible.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] In the short term, toil reduction projects reduce the staff available to address feature requests, performance improvements, and other operational tasks.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] But if the toil reduction is successful, in the long term the team will be healthier and happier, and have more time for engineering improvements.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] It is important for everyone in the organization to agree that toil reduction is a worthwhile goal.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Manager support is crucial in defending staff from new demands.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Use objective metrics about toil to make the case for pushback.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] To create strong business cases for toil reduction, look for opportunities to couple your strategy with other desirable features or business goals.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] If a complementary goal—for example, security, scalability, or reliability—is compelling to your customers, they’ll be more willing to give up their current toil-generating systems for shiny new ones that aren’t as toil intentive.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Then, reducing toil is just a nice side effect of helping users!
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Don’t try to design the perfect system that eliminates all toil.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Automate a few high-priority items first, and then improve your solution using the time you gained by eliminating that toil, applying the lessons learned along the way.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Pick clear metrics such as MTTR (Mean Time to Repair) to measure your success.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] At scale, a diverse production environment becomes exponentially harder to manage.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Special devices require time-consuming and error-prone ongoing management and incident response.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] You can use the “pets versus cattle” approach5 to add redundancy and enforce consistency in your environment.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Choosing what to consider cattle depends on the needs and scale of an organization.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] It may be reasonable to evaluate network links, switches, machines, racks of machines, or even entire clusters as interchangeable units.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Shifting devices to a cattle philosophy may have a high initial cost, but can reduce the cost of maintenance, disaster recovery, and resource utilization in the medium to long term.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Equipping multiple devices with the same interface implies that they have consistent configuration, are interchangeable, and require less maintenance.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] A consistent interface (to divert traffic, restore traffic, perform a shutdown, etc.) for a variety of devices allows for more flexible and scalable automation.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Google aligns business incentives to encourage engineering teams to unify across our ever-evolving toolkit of internal technologies and tools.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Teams are free to choose their own approaches, but they have to own the toil generated by unsupported tools or legacy systems.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Automation can save countless hours in human labor, but in the wrong circumstances, it can also trigger outages.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] In general, defensive software is always a good idea; when automation wields admin-level powers, defensive software is crucial.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Every action should be assessed for its safety before execution.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] This includes changes that might reduce serving capacity or redundancy.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Once you identify a piece of toil as automatable, it’s worthwhile to consider how to best mirror the human workflow in software.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] You rarely want to literally transcribe a human workflow into a machine workflow.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Also note that automation shouldn’t eliminate human understanding of what’s going wrong.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Once your process is thoroughly documented, try to break down the manual work into components that can be implemented separately and used to create a composable software library that other automation projects can reuse later.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] As the upcoming datacenter repair case study illustrates, automation often provides the opportunity to reevaluate and simplify human workflows.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Sometimes you don’t have to do all of the work to reduce toil yourself.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Many efforts like one-off migrations may not justify building their own bespoke tooling, but you’re probably not the first organization to tread this path.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Look for opportunities to use or extend third-party or open source libraries to reduce development costs, or at least to help you transition to partial automation.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] It’s important to actively seek feedback from other people who interact with your tools, workflows, and automation.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Your users will make different assumptions about your tools depending on their understanding of the underlying systems.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] The less familiar your users are with these systems, the more important it is to actively seek feedback from users.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Leverage surveys, user experience (UX) studies, and other mechanisms to understand how your tools are used, and integrate this feedback to produce more effective automation in the future.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Human input is only one dimension of feedback you should consider.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Also measure the effectiveness of automated tasks according to metrics like latency, error rate, rework rate, and human time saved (across all groups involved in the process).
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Ideally, find high-level measures you can compare before and after any automation or toil reduction efforts.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] The following case studies illustrate the strategies for toil reduction just discussed.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Each story describes an important area of Google’s infrastructure that reached a point at which it could no longer scale sublinearly with human effort; over time, an increasing number of engineer hours resulted in smaller returns on that investment.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Much of that effort you’ll now recognize as toil.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] For each case study, we detail how the engineers identified, assessed, and mitigated that toil.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] We also discuss the results and the lessons we learned along the way.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] In the first case study, Google’s datacenter networking had a scaling problem: we had a massive number of Google-designed components and links to monitor, mitigate, and repair.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] We needed a strategy to minimize the toilsome nature of this work for datacenter technicians.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] The second case study focuses on a team running their own “outlier” specialized hardware to support toil-intensive business processes that had become deeply entrenched within Google.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] This case study illustrates benefits of reevaluating and replacing operationally expensive business processes.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] It demonstrates that with a little persistence and perseverance, it’s possible to move to alternatives even when constrained by the institutional inertia of a large organization.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Taken together, these case studies provide a concrete example of each toil reduction strategy covered earlier.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Each case study begins with a list of relevant toil reduction strategies.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] This case study takes place in Google’s datacenters.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Similar to all datacenters, Google’s machines are connected to switches, which are connected to routers.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Traffic flows in and out from these routers via links that in turn connect to other routers on the internet.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] As Google’s requirements for handling internet traffic grew, the number of machines required to serve that traffic increased dramatically.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Our datacenters grew in scope and complexity as we figured out how to serve a large amount of traffic efficiently and economically.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] This growth changed the nature of datacenter manual repairs from occasional and interesting to frequent and rote—two signals of toil.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] When Google first began running its own datacenters, each datacenter’s network topology featured a small number of network devices that managed traffic to a large number of machines.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] A single network device failure could significantly impact network performance, but a relatively small team of engineers could handle troubleshooting the small number of devices.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] At this early stage, engineers debugged problems and shifted traffic away from failed components manually.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Our next-generation datacenter had significantly more machines and introduced software-defined networking (SDN) with a folded Clos topology which greatly increased the number of switches.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Figure 6-2 shows the complexity of traffic flow for a small datacenter Clos switch network.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] This proportionately larger number of devices meant that a larger number of components could now fail.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] While each individual failure had less impact on network performance than before, the sheer volume of issues began to overwhelm the engineering staff.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] In addition to introducing a heavy load of new problems to debug, the complex layout was confusing to technicians: Which exact links needed to be checked?
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Which line card6 did they need to replace?
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] What was a Stage 2 switch, versus a Stage 1 or Stage 3 switch?
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Would shutting down a switch create problems for users?
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Repairing failed datacenter line cards was one obvious growing work backlog, so we targeted this task as our first stage of creating datacenter network repair automation.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] This case study describes how we introduced repair automation for our first generation of line cards (named Saturn).
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] We then discuss the improvements we introduced with the next generation of line cards for Jupiter fabrics.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Shift traffic away from the failed device (a “drain” operation).
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Perform a reboot or repair (such as replacing a line card).
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Shift traffic back to the device (an “undrain” operation).
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] This unvarying and repetitive work of draining, undraining, and repairing devices is a textbook example of toil.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] The repetitive nature of the work introduced problems of its own—for example, engineers might multitask by working on a line card while also debugging more challenging problems.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] As a result, the distracted engineer might accidentally introduce an unconfigured switch back to the network.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Instead of assigning every issue to an engineer for risk assessment, drain, undrain, and validation, we decided to create a framework for automation that, when coupled with an on-site technician where appropriate, could support these operations programmatically.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Our high-level goal was to build a system that would respond to problems detected on network devices, rather than relying on an engineer to triage and fix these problems.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Instead of sending a “line card down” alert to an engineer, we wrote the software to request a drain (to remove traffic) and create a case for a technician.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] The repair service picks up the problem and enables repairs on the switch.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] The workflow manager detects the new case and sends it to a pool of repair cases for a technician to claim.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] The automated repair system brings the line card up again.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] After a pause to give the card time to initialize, the workflow manager triggers an operation to restore traffic to the switch and close the repair case.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] The new system freed the engineering team from a large volume of toilsome work, giving them more time to pursue productive projects elsewhere: working on Jupiter, the next-generation Clos topology.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Capacity requirements in the datacenter continued to double almost every 12 months.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] As a result, our next-generation datacenter fabric, Jupiter, was more than six times larger than any previous Google fabric.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] The volume of problems was also six times larger.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Jupiter presented scaling challenges for repair automation because thousands of fiber links and hundreds of line cards could fail in each layer.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] Fortunately, the increase in potential failure points was accompanied by far greater redundancy, which meant we could implement more ambitious automation.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p01] We adopted a simple and uniform workflow for every line-card problem on Jupiter switches: declare the switch down, drain it, and begin a repair.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] The repair service picks up the problem and enables repairs on the switch: drain the entire switch, and add a drain reason.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Attempt (via two distinct methods) to power-cycle the switch.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] If this was the second failure, send the case directly to the technician, requesting new hardware.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] After the hardware change occurs, run automated verification and then install and configure the switch.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Remove the repair reason, clear the problem from the database, and undrain the switch.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] This new workflow management was a complete rewrite of the previous repair system.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] The next logical improvement was to automate mitigation and repair of memory errors on Jupiter switch line cards.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] As shown in Figure 6-6, prior to automation, this workflow depended heavily on an engineer to determine if the failure was hardware- or software-related, and then to drain and reboot the switch or arrange a repair if appropriate.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Our automation simplified the repair workflow by no longer attempting to troubleshoot memory errors (see Sometimes imperfect automation is good enough for why this made sense).
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Instead, we treated memory errors the same way we handled failed line cards.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] To extend automation to memory errors, we simply had to add another symptom to a config file to make it act on the new problem type.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Figure 6-7 depicts the automated workflow for memory errors.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] During the several years we worked to automate network repair, we learned a lot of general lessons about how to effectively reduce toil.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] For Saturn-based line cards, replacing a line card required draining the entire switch.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Draining the entire switch early in the repair process meant losing the working capacity of all line cards on the switch while waiting for replacement parts and a technician.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] We introduced a button in the UI called “Prep component” that allowed a technician to drain traffic from the entire switch right before they were ready to replace the card, thereby eliminating unnecessary downtime for the rest of the switch (see “Push prep button to drain switch” in Figure 6-5).
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] In response to user reports and problems with regressions caused by the complexity of the feature, we designed future workflows to ensure the switch was safe and ready for repair before the technician arrived at the switch.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] We leaned too heavily on experienced datacenter technicians to identify errors in our system (for example, when the software indicated it was safe to proceed with repairs, but the switch was actually undrained).
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] These technicians also had to perform several tasks manually, without being prompted by automation.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] In one particularly high-impact episode, a technician decided to expedite the “press button and wait for results” experience by initiating concurrent drains on every line card waiting for repairs at the datacenter, resulting in network congestion and user-visible packet loss.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Our software didn’t anticipate and prevent this action because we didn’t test the automation with new technicians.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Where possible, avoid monolithic designs.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Build complex automation workflows from separable components, each of which handles a distinct and well-defined task.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] We could easily reuse or adapt key components of our early Jupiter automation for each successive generation of fabric, and it was easier to add new features when we could build on automation that already existed.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Successive variations on Jupiter-type fabrics could leverage work done in earlier iterations.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] We overanalyzed the memory error problem for Jupiter line cards.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] In our attempts at precise diagnosis, we sought to distinguish software errors (fixable by reboots) from hardware errors (which required card replacement), and also to identify errors that impacted traffic versus errors that did not.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] We spent nearly three years (2012–2015) collecting data on over 650 discrete memory error problems before realizing this exercise was probably overkill, or at least shouldn’t block our repair automation project.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Once we decided to act upon any error we detected, it was straightforward to use our existing repair automation to implement a simple policy of draining, rebooting, and reinstalling switches in response to memory errors.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] If the problem recurred, we concluded that the failure was likely hardware-based and requested component replacement.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] We gathered data over the course of a quarter and discovered that most of the errors were transient—most switches recovered after being rebooted and reinstalled.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] We didn’t need additional data to perform the repair, so the three-year delay in implementing the automation was unnecessary.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] While the ability to verify links with BERT before undraining them was handy, BERT tooling didn’t support network management links.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] We added these links into the existing link repair automation with a check that allowed them to skip verification.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] We were comfortable bypassing verification because the links didn’t carry customer traffic, and we could add this functionality later if verification turned out to be important.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Automation can have a very long lifetime, so make sure to plan for project continuity as people leave and join the team.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] New engineers should be trained on legacy systems so they can fix bugs.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Due to parts shortages for Jupiter fabrics, Saturn-based fabrics lived on long after the originally targeted end-of-life date, requiring us to introduce some improvements quite late in Saturn’s overall lifespan.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Once adopted, automation may become entrenched for a long time, with positive and negative consequences.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] When possible, design your automation to evolve in a flexible way.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Relying on inflexible automation makes systems brittle to change.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Policy-based automation can help by clearly separating intent from a generic implementation engine, allowing automation to evolve more transparently.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] After building new tools for Jupiter that determined the risk of a drain operation before executing it, the complexity we encountered led us to introduce a secondary check for defense in depth.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] The second check established an upper limit for the number of impacted links, and another limit for impacted devices.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] If we exceeded either threshold, a tracking bug to request further investigation opened automatically.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] We tuned these limits over time to reduce false positives.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Repair automation can sometimes fail, especially when first introduced.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Management support is crucial in preserving the project and empowering the team to persevere.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] We recommend establishing an error budget for antitoil automation.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] You should also explain to external stakeholders that automation is essential despite the risk of failures, and that it enables continuous improvement in reliability and efficiency.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Ultimately, the complexity of scenarios to be automated is the real hurdle to overcome.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Reexamine the system before you work on automating it—can you simplify the system or workflow first?
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Pay attention to all aspects of the workflow you are automating, not just the aspects that create toil for you personally.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Conduct testing with the people directly involved in the work and actively seek their feedback and assistance.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] If they make mistakes, find out how your UI could be clearer, or what additional safety checks you need.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Make sure your automation doesn’t create new toil—for example, by opening unnecessary tickets that need human attention.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Creating problems for other teams will increase resistance to future automation endeavors.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] In the early days of Google, the Corp Data Storage (CDS) SRE team provided home directories to all Googlers.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Similar to Active Directory’s Roaming Profiles, common in Enterprise IT, Googlers could use the same home directories across workstations and platforms.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] The CDS team also offered “Team Shares” for cross-team collaboration in a shared storage space.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] We provided home directories and Team Shares via a fleet of Netapp Storage Appliances over NFS/CIFS (or “filers”).
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] This storage was operationally expensive but provided a much-needed service to Googlers.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] As years passed, these filer solutions were mostly deprecated by other, better, storage solutions: our version control systems (Piper9/Git-on-borg10), Google Drive, Google Team Drive, Google Cloud Storage, and an internal, shared, globally distributed filesystem called x20.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Most relevant to this chapter, home directories and Team Shares were toil-intensive.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Many facets of storage provisioning were ticket-driven.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Although these workflows were often partially scripted, they represented a sizable amount of the CDS team’s toil.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] We spent a lot of time creating and configuring shares, modifying access, troubleshooting end user issues, and performing turnups and turndowns to manage capacity.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] CDS also managed the provisioning, racking, and cabling processes for this specialized hardware, in addition to their configuration, updates, and backups.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Due to latency requirements, we often had to deploy in remote offices instead of Google datacenters—which sometimes required a team member to travel a substantial distance to manage a deployment.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] First, we gathered data: CDS created a tool called Moonwalk to analyze how employees used our services.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Another compelling business reason led us to move away from filers: if we could migrate most of our filer use cases to G Suite/GCP, then we could use the lessons we learned to improve these products, thereby enabling other large enterprises to migrate to G Suite/GCP.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] No single alternative could meet all of the current filer use cases.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] However, by breaking the problem into smaller addressable components, we found that in aggregate, a handful of alternatives could cover all of our use cases.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] The alternative solutions were more specialized, but each provided a better user experience than a generalized filer-powered solution.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] As we catalogued use cases and found alternatives, the decommissioning plan took shape.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] This case study focuses on the first project, Moira.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] The subsequent projects built upon what we learned from and created for Moira.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] As shown in Figure 6-8, Moira consisted of four phases.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] The first step to retiring a legacy system is to stop or (often more realistically) to slow or discourage new adoption.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] It’s much more painful to take something away from users than never offer it in the first place.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Moonwalk data showed that nonengineering Googlers used their shared home directories the least, so our initial phase targeted these users.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] As the phases grew in scope, so did our confidence in the alternative storage solutions and our migration processes and tooling.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Each phase of the project had an associated design document that examined the proposal along dimensions like security, scalability, testing, and launch.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] We also paid special attention to user experience, expectations, and communication.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Our goal was making sure that users affected by each phase understood the reasons for the decommissioning project and the easiest way to archive or migrate their data.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] While we had basic statistics about our users’ shares (share sizes, for example), we needed to understand our users’ workflows to help drive business decisions around the deprecation.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] We set up a system called Moonwalk to gather and report this information.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Moonwalk stored the data about who was accessing what files and when in BigQuery, which allowed us to create reports and perform ad hoc queries to understand our users better.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Using BigQuery, we summarized access patterns across 2.5 billion files using 300 terabytes of disk space.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] This data was owned by 60,000 POSIX users in 400 disk volumes on 124 NAS appliances in 60 geographic sites around the world.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Our large user base made managing the home directory decommissioning effort with a manual ticket-based process untenable.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] We needed to make the entire process—surveying users, communicating the reasons for the decommissioning project, and walking through either archiving their data or migrating to an alternative—as low-touch as possible.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Our business logic became fairly complicated because we had to account for a number of user scenarios.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] For example, a user might leave Google, go on a temporary leave, or have data under a litigation hold.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Figure 6-9 provides a sample design doc state diagram illustrating this complexity.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] The technology powering the portal was relatively simple.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Written in Python with the Flask framework, it read and wrote to a Bigtable, and used a number of background jobs and schedulers to manage its work.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] We needed a lot of ancillary tooling to glue the portal and configuration management together, and to query and communicate with users.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] We also needed to be sure we identified the right users for the right communications.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] False positives (erroneously reporting action required) or false negatives (failing to notify a user that you were taking something away) were both unacceptable, and errors here would mean extra work in the form of lost credibility and customer service.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] We worked with alternative storage system owners to add features to their roadmaps.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] As a result, less mature alternatives became more suitable for filer use cases as the project progressed.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] We could also use and extend tooling from other teams.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] For example, we used another team’s internally developed tool to migrate data from Google Cloud Storage to Google Drive as part of the Portal’s auto-archiving functionality.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] The effort required substantial software development over the life of the project.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] We built and iterated upon each component—the Moonwalk reporting pipeline, the portal, and the automation to better manage retiring and archiving shares—in response to the next phase’s requirements and user feedback.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] We approached a feature-complete state only in phase three (almost two years in); and even then, we needed additional tooling to handle a “long tail” of around 800 users.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] This low and slow approach had definite benefits.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] As with all engineering decisions, there were tradeoffs: the project would be long-lived, so the team had to endure filer-related operational toil while engineering these solutions.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] The program officially completed in 2016.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] We’ve reduced home directories from 65,000 to around 50 at the time of writing.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] (The current Azog Project aims to retire these last users and fully decommission the filer hardware.) Our users’ experience has improved, and CDS has retired operationally expensive hardware and processes.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] While no one alternative could replace the filer-backed storage that Googlers had used for 14+ years, we didn’t necessarily need a wholesale replacement.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] By effectively moving up the stack from a generalized but limited filesystem-level solution to multiple application-specific solutions, we traded flexibility for improved scalability, latency tolerance, and security.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] The Moira team had to anticipate a variety of user journeys and consider alternatives in various stages of maturity.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] We had to manage expectations around these alternatives: in aggregate, they could provide a better user experience, but getting there wouldn’t be painless.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] We learned the following lessons about effectively reducing toil along the way.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Business requirements drift and new solutions continuously emerge, so it’s worthwhile to periodically question toil-intensive business processes.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] As we discussed in Toil Management Strategies, rejecting toil (deciding not to perform toilsome tasks) is often the simplest way to eliminate it, even though this approach isn’t always quick or easy.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Shore up your case with user analytics and business justifications beyond mere toil reduction.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] The primary business justification for filer decommissioning came down to the benefits of a Beyond Corp security model.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] So, while Moira was a great way to reduce the CDS team’s toil, emphasizing the many security benefits of decommissioning filers made for a more compelling business case.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] We built a custom portal for Moira (which was relatively expensive), but there are often easier alternatives.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Many teams at Google manage and configure their services using version control, and process organizational requests in the form of pull requests (called changelists, or CLs).
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] This approach requires little or no involvement from the service’s team, but gives us the benefits of code review and continuous deployment processes to validate, test, and deploy internal service configuration changes.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] At several points, the Moira team used an “engineer behind the curtain” approach that married automation with manual work by engineers.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] For example, share requests opened tracking bugs, which our automation updated as we processed the requests.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] The system also assigned end users bugs to remind them to address their shares.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Tickets can serve as a quick and dirty GUI for automation: they keep a log of work, update stakeholders, and provide a simple human fallback mechanism if automation goes awry.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] In our case, if a user needed help with their migration or if automation couldn’t process their request, the bug was automatically routed to a queue that SREs handled manually.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Moira’s engineers chose to retool our automation to either handle share edge cases specifically, or to delete/modify nonconforming shares to match expectations of tooling.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] This allowed us to approach zero-touch automation for much of the migration processes.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Look for ways to nudge new users to adopt better (and hopefully less toil-intensive) alternatives.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] In this vein, Moira required escalations for new share or quota requests and recognized users who retired their shares.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] It’s also important to provide good documentation around service setup, best practices, and when to use your service.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Google teams frequently employ codelabs or cookbooks that teach users how to set up and use their service for common use cases.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] As a result, most user onboarding doesn’t require help from the team that owns the service.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] At minimum, the amount of toil associated with running a production service grows linearly with its complexity and scale.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Automation is often the gold standard of toil elimination, and can be combined with a number of other tactics.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Even when toil isn’t worth the effort of full automation, you can decrease engineering and operations workloads through strategies like partial automation or changing business processes.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] The patterns and methods for eliminating toil described in this chapter can be generalized to work for a variety of other large-scale production services.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Eliminating toil frees up engineering time to focus on the more enduring aspects of services, and allows teams to keep manual tasks at a minimum as the complexity and scale of modern service architectures continue to increase.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] It’s important to note that eliminating toil isn’t always the best solution.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] As mentioned throughout this chapter, you should consider the measurable costs associated with identifying, designing, and implementing processes or automation solutions around toil.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Once you identify toil, it's crucial to determine when toil reduction makes sense, using metrics, return on investment (ROI) analysis, risk assessment, and iterative development.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Toil usually starts small, and can rapidly grow to consume an entire team.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] SRE teams must be relentless in eliminating toil, because even if the task seems daunting, the benefits usually exceed the costs.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Each of the projects we described required perseverance and dedication from its respective teams, who sometimes battled skepticism or institutional resistance, and who always faced competing high priorities.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] We hope these stories encourage you to identify your toil, quantify it, and then work toward eliminating it.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Even if you can’t invest in a big project today, you can start with a small proof of concept that can help change your team’s willingness to deal with toil.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] 1Whether something is automatable is the most subjective characteristic listed here; your perspective will evolve as you gain experience by automating away toil.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] 2Some engineers do not mind working on toil for a prolonged period—not everyone’s tolerance threshold for toil is the same.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Over the longer term, toil causes career stagnation while promoting burnout-induced turnover.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] A certain level of toil is unavoidable, but we recommend reducing it where feasible—for the health of the team, the service, and individuals alike.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] 3In other words, if a service and its nine dependencies each have 99.99% availability, the aggregate availability of the service will be 0.999910 = 99.9%.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] For further reading on how dependencies factor into service availability, see "The Calculus of Service Availability".
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] 4Of course, you won’t be able to handle some one-off cases via self-service (“you want a VM with how much RAM?”), but aim to cover the majority of use cases.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Moving 80–90% of requests to self-service is still a huge reduction in workload!
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] 5In short, moving away from individual specialized devices toward a fleet of devices with a common interface.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] See Case Study 1: Reducing Toil in the Datacenter with Automation for a detailed explanation of this analogy.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] 6A line card is a modular component that usually provides multiple interfaces to the network.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] It is seated in the backplane of a chassis along with other line cards and components.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Modular network switches consist of a chassis that includes a backplane, power entry modules, control card module, and one or more line cards.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] Each line card supports network connections either to machines or other line cards (in other switches).
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] As with a USB network interface adapter, you can replace any line card without powering down the whole switch, provided the line card has been “drained,” meaning that the other interfaces have been told to stop sending traffic to it.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] 7Bit error rate test: check for unhealthy links before restoring service.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] 9Piper is Google’s internal version control system.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] For more information, see Rachel Potvin and Josh Levenberg, “Why Google Stores Billions of Lines of Code in a Single Repository,” Communications of the ACM 59, no.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] 10Google also has scalable self-service Git hosting for code that doesn’t live in Piper.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] 11Beyond Corp is an initiative to move from a traditional perimeter-based security model to a cryptographic identity-based model.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] When a Google laptop connects to an internal Google service, the service verifies trust through a combination of a cryptographic certificate identifying the laptop, a second factor owned by the user (such as a USB security key), the client device config/state, and the user’s credentials.
[src:runbook-automation/eliminating-toil-p02] 12x20 is an internal globally shared, highly available filesystem with POSIX-like filesystem semantics.
[src:runbook-automation/it-service-management] Organizational ITSM process execution, especially for workflows, can benefit significantly from being supported with specialized software tools.
[src:runbook-automation/it-service-management] A service desk is a primary IT function within the discipline of IT service management (ITSM) as defined by ITIL.
[src:runbook-automation/it-service-management] It is intended to provide a *Single Point of Contact* (SPOC) to meet the communication needs of both users and IT staff, and to satisfy both customer and IT provider objectives.
[src:runbook-automation/it-service-management] *User* refers to the actual user of the service, while *customer* refers to the entity that is paying for the service.
[src:runbook-automation/it-service-management] ITSM tools are frequently applied to other aspects of business; this practice is often called enterprise service management (ESM).
[src:runbook-automation/it-service-management] A key initiative in ITSM is the automation of routine tasks, enabling personnel to focus on higher-priority responsibilities; this is known as IT process automation.
[src:runbook-automation/it-service-management] The ITIL approach considers the service desk to be the central point of contact between service providers and users/customers on a day-to-day basis.
[src:runbook-automation/it-service-management] It is also a focal point for reporting *incidents* (disruptions or potential disruptions in service availability or quality) and for submitting *service requests* (routine requests for services).
[src:runbook-automation/it-service-management] ITIL regards a call center or help desk as similar kinds of tech support which provide only a portion of what a service desk can offer.
[src:runbook-automation/it-service-management] A service desk has a broader and user-centered approach which is designed to provide the user with an informed single point of contact for all IT activities.
[src:runbook-automation/it-service-management] A service desk facilitates the integration of business processes into the service management infrastructure.
[src:runbook-automation/it-service-management] Computer emergency response teams (CERT) are specifically dedicated to computer security incidents.
[src:runbook-automation/it-service-management] ITSM is similar to other IT and general management approaches, especially information security management and software engineering.
[src:runbook-automation/it-service-management] Consequently, IT service management frameworks have been influenced by other standards and adopted concepts from them, e.g.
[src:runbook-automation/it-service-management] There are international, chapter-based professional associations, such as the IT Service Management Forum (itSMF), and HDI.
[src:runbook-automation/it-service-management] These organizations' main goal is to foster the exchange of experiences and ideas between ITSM users.
[src:runbook-automation/it-service-management] To this end, national and local itSMF and HDI chapters (LIGs or local interest groups for itSMF) organize conferences and workshops.
[src:runbook-automation/it-service-management] Some of them also contribute to the translation of ITSM framework documents into their respective languages or publish their own ITSM guides.
[src:runbook-automation/it-service-management] There are several service management certifications that include, but are not limited to, ITILv4, TOGAF or COBIT.
[src:runbook-automation/runbook] In a computer system or network, a **runbook** is a compilation of routine procedures and operations that the system administrator or operator carries out.
[src:runbook-automation/runbook] System administrators in IT departments and NOCs use runbooks as a reference.
[src:runbook-automation/runbook] Runbooks can be in either electronic or in physical book form.
[src:runbook-automation/runbook] Typically, a runbook contains procedures to begin, stop, supervise, and debug the system.
[src:runbook-automation/runbook] It may also describe procedures for handling special requests and contingencies.
[src:runbook-automation/runbook] An effective runbook allows other operators, with prerequisite expertise, to effectively manage and troubleshoot a system.
[src:runbook-automation/runbook] Through runbook automation, these processes can be carried out using software tools in a predetermined manner.
[src:runbook-automation/runbook] In addition to automating IT specific processes, the results of the runbook can be presented on-screen back to the user or Service Desk engineer.
[src:runbook-automation/runbook] Multiple runbooks can be linked together using a Decision Tree to provide users with interactive troubleshooting and guided procedures.
[src:runbook-automation/runbook] Operational runbooks may be tied to ITIL incidents to allow repeatable processes supporting specific aspects of the service catalog.
[src:runbook-automation/runbook] The runbook is typically divided into routine automated processes and routine manual processes.
[src:runbook-automation/runbook] The runbook catalog begins with an index of processes covered and may be broken down in outline form to align the processes to the major elements they support in the service catalog.
[src:runbook-automation/runbook] A runbook is a compilation of routine procedures and operations that the system administrator or operator carries out.
[src:runbook-automation/runbook] The documentation for running a task, whether in electronic or paper form, is called a runbook.
[src:runbook-automation/runbook] Sometimes written as "run book," it may supplement bullet-pointed steps with error messages (and what to do) and flowcharts.
[src:runbook-automation/runbook] A runbook workflow can potentially interact with all types of infrastructure elements, such as applications, databases, and hardware - using a variety of communication methods such as command-line interfaces (CLI), HTTP REST and SOAP API's, SSH sessions, scripts, utilities, and code libraries.
[src:runbook-automation/runbook] According to Gartner, the growth of RBA has coincided with the need for IT operations executives to enhance IT operations efficiency measures—including reducing mean time to repair (MTTR), increasing mean time between failures (MTBF), and automating the provisioning of IT resources.
[src:runbook-automation/runbook] Patents have been granted for various aspects of producing, improving, and using runbooks.
[src:runbook-automation/runbook] Some tools can incorporate a front-end or presentation layer (to the runbook) so that the results of the automated tasks are presented on-screen, sometimes even with red/amber/green traffic lights to visualise if a specific task completed successfully, or failed to execute correctly.
[src:runbook-automation/runbook] More advanced runbook automation platforms incorporate dashboards, analytics and audit trails for regulatory reporting.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] In computing, a **script** is a relatively short and simple set of instructions that typically automate an otherwise manual process.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] The act of writing a script is called **scripting**.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] A **scripting language** or **script language** is a programming language that is used for scripting.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] Originally, scripting was limited to automating shells in operating systems, and languages were relatively simple.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] Today, scripting is more pervasive and some scripting languages include modern features that allow them to be used to develop application software also.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] A scripting language can be a general-purpose programming language or a domain-specific language for a given environment.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] When embedded in an application, it may be called an *extension language*.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] A scripting language is sometimes referred to as very high-level programming language if it operates at a high level of abstraction, or as a *control language*, especially for job control languages on mainframe computers.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] The term *scripting language* is sometimes used in a wider sense, to refer to dynamic high-level programming languages in general.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] Some are strictly interpreted languages, while others use a form of compilation.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] In this context, the term *script* refers to a small program in such a language.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] Typically, a script is contained in a single file, and no larger than a few thousand lines of code.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] The scope of scripting languages ranges from small to large, and from highly domain-specific language to general-purpose programming languages.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] A language may start as small and highly domain-specific and later develop into a portable and general-purpose language; conversely, a general-purpose language may later develop special domain-specific dialects.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] Script is a subjective characterization that generally includes the following attributes.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] A script is usually not compiled, at least not its usual meaning.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] Generally, they are interpreted directly from source code, or from bytecode, or run as native after just-in-time compilation.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] A script is generally relatively short and simple.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] As there is no limit on size or complexity, script is subjective.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] A few lines of code without branching is probably considered a script.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] A codebase of multiple files, that performs sophisticated user or hardware interface or complicated algorithms or multiprogramming is probably not considered a script.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] A script usually automates a task that would otherwise be performed by a person in a more manual way.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] A language that is primarily intended for scripting generally has limited capabilities compared to a general-purpose language.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] A scripting language may lack the functionality to write complex applications.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] Typically, a script starts executing at the first line of code whereas an application typically starts at a special point in the code called the entry point.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] For example, Java is not script-like since an application starts at the function named `main` which need not be at the top of the code.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] The following code starts at `main`, then calls `printHelloWorld` which prints "Hello World".
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] In contrast, the following Python code prints "Hello World" without the `main` function or other syntax such as a class definition required by Java.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] Scripts are often created or modified by the person executing them, but they are also often distributed, such as when large portions of games are written in a scripting language, notably the Google Chrome T-rex game.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] Early mainframe computers (in the 1950s) were non-interactive, instead using batch processing.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] IBM's Job Control Language (JCL) is the archetype of languages used to control batch processing.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] The first interactive shells were developed in the 1960s to enable remote operation of the first time-sharing systems, and these used shell scripts, which controlled running computer programs within a computer program, the shell.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] Calvin Mooers in his TRAC language is generally credited with inventing *command substitution*, the ability to embed commands in scripts that, when interpreted, insert a character string into the script.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] Louis Pouzin wrote an early processor for command scripts called RUNCOM for CTSS around 1964.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] Stuart Madnick at MIT wrote a scripting language for IBM's CP/CMS in 1966.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] He originally called this processor COMMAND, later named EXEC.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] Multics included an offshoot of CTSS RUNCOM, also called RUNCOM.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] EXEC was eventually replaced by EXEC 2 and Rexx.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] Languages such as Tcl and Lua were specifically designed as general-purpose scripting languages that could be embedded in any application.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] Other languages such as Visual Basic for Applications (VBA) provided strong integration with the automation facilities of an underlying system.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] Embedding of such general-purpose scripting languages instead of developing a new language for each application also had obvious benefits, relieving the application developer of the need to code a language translator from scratch and allowing the user to apply skills learned elsewhere.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] Some software incorporates several different scripting languages.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] Modern web browsers typically provide a language for writing extensions to the browser itself, and several standard embedded languages for controlling the browser, including JavaScript (a dialect of ECMAScript) or XUL.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] Scripting languages can be categorized into several different types, with a considerable degree of overlap among the types.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] Scripting is often contrasted with system programming, as in Ousterhout's dichotomy or "programming in the large and programming in the small".
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] In this view, scripting is glue code, connecting software components, and a language specialized for this purpose is a *glue language*.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] Pipelines and shell scripting are archetypal examples of glue languages, and Perl was initially developed to fill this same role.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] Web development can be considered a use of glue languages, interfacing between a database and web server.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] But if a substantial amount of logic is written in script, it is better characterized as simply another software component, not "glue".
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] Macro languages exposed to operating system or application components can serve as glue languages.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] These include Visual Basic for Applications, WordBasic, LotusScript, CorelScript, Hummingbird Basic, QuickScript, Rexx, SaxBasic, and WinWrap Basic.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] Other tools like AWK can also be considered glue languages, as can any language implemented by a Windows Script Host engine (VBScript, JScript and VBA by default in Windows and third-party engines including implementations of Rexx, Perl, Tcl, Python, XSLT, Ruby, Modern Pascal, Delphi, and C).
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] A majority of applications can access and use operating system components via the object models or its own functions.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] Depending upon the OS version, WSH and the default script engines (VBScript and JScript) are available.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] Programmable calculators can be programmed in glue languages in three ways.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] For example, the Texas Instruments TI-92, by factory default can be programmed with a command script language.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] Inclusion of the scripting and glue language Lua in the TI-NSpire series of calculators could be seen as a successor to this.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] The primary on-board high-level programming languages of most graphing calculators (most often Basic variants, sometimes Lisp derivatives, and more uncommonly, C derivatives) in many cases can glue together calculator functions—such as graphs, lists, matrices, etc.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] Third-party implementations of more comprehensive Basic version that may be closer to variants listed as glue languages in this article are available—and attempts to implement Perl, Rexx, or various operating system shells on the TI and HP graphing calculators are also mentioned.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] A number of text editors support macros written either using a macro language built into the editor, e.g., The SemWare Editor (TSE), vi improved (VIM), or using an external implementation, e.g., XEDIT, or both, e.g., KEDIT.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] Sometimes text editors and edit macros are used under the covers to provide other applications, e.g., FILELIST and RDRLIST in CMS .
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] Many of these languages' interpreters double as command-line interpreters such as the Unix shell or the MS-DOS `COMMAND.COM`.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] Others, such as AppleScript offer the use of English-like commands to build scripts.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] With the advent of graphical user interfaces, a specialized kind of scripting language emerged for controlling a computer.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] These languages interact with the same graphic windows, menus, buttons, and so on, that a human user would.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] They do this by simulating the actions of a user.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] These languages are typically used to automate user actions.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] Such languages are also called *macros* when control is through simulated key presses or mouse clicks, and tapping or pressing on a touch-activated screen.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] These languages could in principle be used to control any GUI application, but in practice their use is limited because they need support from the application and from the operating system.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] There are a few exceptions to this limit.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] Some GUI scripting languages are based on recognizing graphical objects from their display screen pixels.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] These GUI scripting languages do not depend on support from the operating system or application.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] When the GUI provides the appropriate interfaces, as in the IBM Workplace Shell, a generic scripting language, e.g., Object REXX, can be used to write GUI scripts.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] Likewise, many computer game systems use a custom scripting language to express the programmed actions of non-player characters and the game environment.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] Languages of this sort are designed for a single application; while they may superficially resemble a specific general-purpose language (e.g., QuakeC, modeled after C), they have custom features that distinguish them.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] Emacs Lisp, while a fully formed and capable dialect of Lisp, contains many special features that make it most useful for extending the editing functions of Emacs.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] An application-specific scripting language can be viewed as a domain-specific programming language specialized to one application.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] A number of languages have been designed for the purpose of replacing application-specific scripting languages by being embeddable in application programs.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] The application programmer (working in C or another systems language) includes "hooks" where the scripting language can control the application.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] These languages may be technically equivalent to an application-specific extension language but when an application embeds a "common" language, the user gets the advantage of being able to transfer skills from application to application.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] A more generic alternative is simply to provide a library (often a C library) that a general-purpose language can use to control the application, without modifying the language for the specific domain.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] JavaScript began as, and still is mostly, a language for scripting inside web browsers.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] However, the standardizing of the language as ECMAScript has made it popular as a general-purpose embeddable language.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] The Mozilla implementation SpiderMonkey is embedded in several environments such as the Yahoo Widgets Engine,and applications such as the Adobe products Flash (ActionScript) and Acrobat (for scripting PDF files).
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] Tcl was created as an extension language but has come to be used more often as a general-purpose language in roles similar to Python, Perl, and Ruby.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] In contrast, Rexx was created as a job control language, but is widely used as an extension language and a general-purpose language.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] Perl is a general-purpose language, but had the Oraperl (1990) dialect, consisting of a Perl 4 binary with Oracle Call Interface compiled in.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] This has however since been replaced by a library (Perl Module), DBD::Oracle.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] Other complex and task-oriented applications may incorporate and expose an embedded programming language to allow their users more control and give them more functionality than can be available through a user interface, no matter how sophisticated.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] For example, Autodesk Maya 3D authoring tools embed the Maya Embedded Language, or Blender which uses Python to fill this role.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] Some other types of applications that need faster feature addition or tweak-and-run cycles (e.g. game engines) also use an embedded language.
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] During the development, this allows them to prototype features faster and tweak more freely, without the need for the user to have intimate knowledge of the inner workings of the application or to rebuild it after each tweak (which can take a significant amount of time).
[src:runbook-automation/scripting-language] The scripting languages used for this purpose range from the more common and more famous Lua and Python to lesser-known ones such as AngelScript and Squirrel.
[src:runbook-automation/self-healing] Self-healing may refer to automatic, homeostatic processes of the body that are controlled by physiological mechanisms inherent in the organism.
[src:runbook-automation/self-healing] Disorders of the spirit and the absence of faith can be self-healed.
[src:runbook-automation/self-healing] In a figurative sense, self-healing properties can be ascribed to systems or processes, which by nature or design tend to correct any disturbances brought into them.
[src:runbook-automation/self-healing] Such as the regeneration of the skin after a cut or scrape, or of an entire limb.
[src:runbook-automation/self-healing] The injured party (the living body) repairs the damaged part by itself.
[src:runbook-automation/self-healing] In automated software testing, self-healing refers to techniques that allow automated tests to recover from certain changes in a software application without immediate human intervention.
[src:runbook-automation/self-healing] Such systems are commonly used to address locator or selector breakage in user-interface tests by trying alternative selectors, comparing element attributes, text, accessibility roles, DOM position, visual cues, or historical run data to identify the most likely intended element.
[src:runbook-automation/self-healing] Self-healing is intended to reduce test maintenance caused by frequent user-interface changes, but it can also introduce false healing, where a test continues by interacting with an unintended element; implementations therefore often require logging, review, and validation of healed actions.
[src:runbook-automation/self-healing] Beyond the innate restorative capacities of the physical body, there are many factors of psychological nature that can influence self-healing.
[src:runbook-automation/self-healing] Self-healing may also be achieved through deliberately applied psychological mechanisms.
[src:runbook-automation/self-healing] These approaches may improve the psychological and physical conditions of a person.
[src:runbook-automation/self-healing] Research confirms that this can be achieved through numerous mechanisms, including relaxation, breathing exercises, fitness exercises, imagery, Meditation, Yoga, qigong, tai chi, biofeedback, and various forms of psychotherapy, among other approaches.
[src:runbook-automation/self-healing] Decreases in muscle tension, which can worsen or produce pains in muscles, tendons and joints when there is chronic muscle tension due to stress.
[src:runbook-automation/self-healing] Improved sleep that can be achieved through relaxation, which improves physiological functions.
[src:runbook-automation/self-healing] Improvements in emotional tensions, depression, anger and other emotions that can otherwise impair social relationships and functioning in the workplace, leading to vicious circles of increased psychological symptoms.
[src:runbook-automation/self-healing] Another phrase that often includes self-healing is self-help.
[src:runbook-automation/self-healing] In 2013 Kathryn Schulz examined it as "an $11 billion industry".
[src:runbook-automation/standard-operating-procedure] A **standard operating procedure** (**SOP**) is a standardized way of doing a task or the set of step-by-step instructions that document how it is done.
[src:runbook-automation/standard-operating-procedure] SOPs are compiled by an organization to help workers carry out routine operations.
[src:runbook-automation/standard-operating-procedure] SOPs aim to achieve efficiency, quality output, and uniformity of performance, while reducing miscommunication and failure to comply with industry regulations.
[src:runbook-automation/standard-operating-procedure] Some military services (e.g., in the UK and the UK) use the term ***standing operating procedure***, since a military SOP is often a unit's unique procedure, not one that is standard across units.
[src:runbook-automation/standard-operating-procedure] The word *standard* could suggest that only one (standard) procedure is to be used across all units.
[src:runbook-automation/standard-operating-procedure] The term is sometimes used facetiously to refer to practices that are unconstructive, yet the norm.
[src:runbook-automation/standard-operating-procedure] In the Philippines, for instance, *SOP* is the term for pervasive corruption within the government and its institutions.
[src:runbook-automation/standard-operating-procedure] A single process may be described by one or more SOPs, depending on how many alternatives may apply.
[src:runbook-automation/standard-operating-procedure] In clinical research, the *International Council for Harmonisation* (ICH) defines SOPs as "detailed, written instructions to achieve uniformity of the performance of a specific function".
[src:runbook-automation/standard-operating-procedure] SOPs usually get applied in pharmaceutical processing and for related clinical studies.
[src:runbook-automation/standard-operating-procedure] There the focus is always set on repeated application of unchanged processes and procedures and its documentation, hence supporting the segregation of origins, causes and effects.
[src:runbook-automation/standard-operating-procedure] Further application is with triage, when limited resources get used according to an assessment on ranking, urgence and staffing possibilities.
[src:runbook-automation/standard-operating-procedure] Study director is mainly responsible for SOPs.
[src:runbook-automation/standard-operating-procedure] The Quality Assurance Unit are individuals who are responsible for monitoring whether the study report and tests are meeting the SOP.
[src:runbook-automation/standard-operating-procedure] SOPs can also provide employee with a reference to common business practices, activities or tasks.
[src:runbook-automation/standard-operating-procedure] New employees use an SOP to answer questions without having to interrupt supervisors to ask how an operation is performed.
[src:runbook-automation/standard-operating-procedure] The international quality standard ISO 9001 essentially requires the determination of processes (documented as standard operating procedures) used in any manufacturing process that could affect the quality of the product.
[src:runbook-automation/standard-operating-procedure] Standard Operating Procedures are extensively employed to assist with working safely.
[src:runbook-automation/standard-operating-procedure] They are sometimes called "safe work methods statements" (SWMS, pronounced as 'swims').
[src:runbook-automation/standard-operating-procedure] Their development is usually preceded by various methods of analyzing tasks or jobs to be performed in a workplace, including an approach called job safety analysis, in which hazards are identified and their control methods described.
[src:runbook-automation/standard-operating-procedure] Procedures must be suited to the literacy levels of the user, so the readability of procedures is important.
